{{Infobox games | Name = V South American Games | Logo = SouthAmGames 1994.png | Size = 100 | Optional caption = 1994 South American Games logo | Host city = [[Valencia, Carabobo|Valencia]] | Country = {{Flagcountry|VEN}} | Motto = | Nations participating = 14 | Athletes participating = 1,599 | Events = 19 sports | Opening ceremony = {{Start date|1994|11|19}} | Closing ceremony = {{End date|1994|11|28}} | Officially opened by = [[Rafael Caldera]] | Athlete's Oath = | Judge's Oath = | Torch Lighter = [[Ramón Volcán]] | Stadium = [[Estadio Misael Delgado|Polideportivo Misael Delgado]] | previous = [[1990 South American Games|1990 Lima]] | next = [[1998 South American Games|1998 Cuenca]] }} The '''V [[South American Games]]''' (Spanish: ''Juegos Sudamericanos''; Portuguese: ''Jogos Sul-Americanos'') were a [[multi-sport event]] held in 1994 in [[Valencia, Carabobo|Valencia]], [[Carabobo]], [[Venezuela]], with some events in [[Puerto Cabello]] (boxing, judo, karate, wrestling) and [[Caracas]] (shooting). The Games were organized by the South American Sports Organization ([[ODESUR]]).<ref name=odesur>{{ Citation |last = |first = |date = |title = VALENCIA 94, VENEZUELA - V JUEGOS SURAMERICANOS - Fecha de apertura: 19 de noviembre de 1994 - Fecha de clausura: 28 de noviembre de 1994 |url = http://odesur.org/valencia-94-venezuela/ |publisher = [[ODESUR]] |language = Spanish |accessdate = August 24, 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140315052415/http://www.odesur.org/valencia-94-venezuela/ |archive-date = 2014-03-15 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> An appraisal of the games and detailed medal lists were published elsewhere,<ref name=cada>{{Citation|last= Rodríguez III|first= Ernesto|year= 2010|title= LIBROS DEL CICLO OLÍMPICO ARGENTINO - Libro I de los Juegos Odesur 1978-2010|publisher= Alarco Ediciones|publication-place= Buenos Aires|page= |url= https://www.scribd.com/doc/41949572/Libro-I-Juegos-Odesur-Ernesto-Rodriguez-III|accessdate= June 2, 2012|language= Spanish|isbn= 978-987-1367-18-4|pages= 192|edition= 1st|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120104102158/http://www.scribd.com/doc/41949572/Libro-I-Juegos-Odesur-Ernesto-Rodriguez-III|archive-date= 2012-01-04|dead-url= yes|df= }}</ref> emphasizing the results of the Argentinian teams.
Torch lighter at the [[Estadio Misael Delgado|Polideportivo Misael Delgado]] was local swimmer [[Ramón Volcán]]. Aruba, the Netherlands Antilles, and Panamá had their first appearance at the games, enhancing the number of participating nations to 14.
The games were initially awarded to [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]], but the local officials declined in 1992.
==Medal count== The medal count for these [[South American Games|Games]] is tabulated below. This table is sorted by the number of [[gold medal]]s earned by each country. The number of [[silver medal]]s is taken into consideration next, and then the number of [[bronze medal]]s.
