'''Initiative''' in a [[chess]] position belongs to the player who can make threats that cannot be ignored. He thus puts his opponent in the position of having to use his turns responding to threats rather than making his own.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chess.about.com/od/reference/g/bldefini.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060506002514/http://chess.about.com/od/reference/g/bldefini.htm |archivedate=2006-05-06 |df= }}</ref> A player with the initiative will often seek to maneuver his pieces into more and more advantageous positions as he launches successive attacks. The player who lacks the initiative may seek to regain it through {{chessgloss|counterattack}}.
==Discussion== Due to moving first, [[White and Black in chess|White]] starts the game with the initiative, but it can be lost in the [[opening (chess)|opening]] by accepting a [[gambit]]. Players can also lose initiative by making unnecessary moves that allow the opponent to gain [[Tempo (chess)|tempo]], such as superfluous "preventive" moves intended to guard against certain actions by the opponent, that nonetheless require no specific response by them. The concept of tempo is closely tied to initiative, as players can acquire the initiative or buttress it by gaining a tempo.
The initiative is important in all phases of the game, but more important in the [[chess endgame|endgame]] than in the [[chess middlegame|middlegame]] and more important in the middlegame than in the [[chess opening|opening]] {{harvcol|Euwe|Meiden|1966|pp=xvii,xxii}}. Having the initiative puts the opponent on the defensive.
[[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] [[Larry Evans]] considers four elements of chess: ''[[pawn structure]]'', ''force'' ({{chessgloss|material}}), ''{{chessgloss|space}}'' (controlling the {{chessgloss|center}} and [[chess piece|piece]] {{chessgloss|mobility}}), and ''time''. Time is measured in [[tempo (chess)|tempos]]. Having a time advantage is having the initiative {{harvcol|Evans|1958|p=123}}. The initiative should be kept as long as possible and only given up for another advantage {{harvcol|Capablanca|de Firmian|2006|pp=65–66}}.
==See also== * [[First move advantage in chess]] * [[Tempo (chess)]]
